Looking for a place where you can write your muses to your hearts’ content? Ever wonder if your OC will find a place to fit in? Then look no further!

                                  Welcome to the National Park !

We are a game-verse Pokémon RP group full of fun, friendly, and active members.  Our goal is to provide a comfortable atmosphere where members can write and develop their muses at their own pace, without all the stress of running an indie blog.

In addition to our community of wonderful writers, we offer frequent events, interactive Discord server, unlimited meme opportunities, and a special ‘Member of the Month’ spotlight!

We love welcoming new friends, so why not check us out today?

title: What’s in Mari’s Bag? (Pokemon AU)
body:
With her travel blogging job taking her to many places and regions in the Pokemon World, Mari has to carry much of her life in a year into 2 bags. For her essential stuff (clothes, toiletries, perhaps some food, etc.), she goes with this niffy backpack, while a bit heavy, it’s quite a miracle that she is able to carry all that weight well. When it comes to everything a Pokemon needs and stuff she needs to grab on the go, she will always bring with her a weekender bag as her Trainer Bag. She often carries that on her shoulder with the shoulder strap.

In that bag she has:

  • Important Travel Documents (passport, tickets, IDs, itinerary plan, hotel & flight confirmations, medical papers (often photocopies as not to lose the real stuff), tickets for Pokemon Contests and Performances)
  • Wallet, cash, & credit cards
  • Electronics (smartphone, tablet, laptop, camera, earphones, chargers, adapters, hard drives & their cables, USBs, a USB port, a PowerCube, and a power bank)
  • Notebooks, a notepad, and a pencil case with pens, pencils, an eraser, a correction tape, a ruler, a pair of travel scissors (don’t question her that!), small tape, and highlighters
  • Medical kit (medicine, bandages, all-purpose sanitizing wipes)
  • Pokemon stuff (medicine, berries, TMs & HMs, Poke Balls, stones, assorted items)
  • Spare glasses (no fun in losing one while on a trip)
  • Tissues, hand wipes, and hand sanitizer
  • Scarf (sometimes she has a hat and gloves for colder weather)
  • Snacks that she can pick up quickly (like a granola bar, nuts, candy, etc.)
  • Books and magazines
  • Tissues, hand wipes, and hand sanitizer
  • Feminine products (really important!)
  • Beauty kit (lipstick, lip gloss, face powder, nail clipper, nail file, hand lotion, perfume, blotting sheets, hair ties, comb & brush, lip balm, dental stuff (toothbrush, toothpaste, dental floss, and mouth wash))

summary: Gen V is absolutely my favorite gen
body:
Gen V is absolutely my favorite gen

I used to think it was IV but that’s because I played it the most and didn’t remember V. The story is great, the legendary Pokemon aren’t gods (it’s not bad if they are, but it’s easier to swallow catching a Pokemon that didn’t help create the universe), the Pokemon designs are interesting, my favorite mechanic changes occurred in this gen (I’ll make a different post about them cause this is getting long and rambling), and the gym designs are interesting and creative on the outside and inside.

summary: Pokemon Card of the Day #1539: Vanilluxe (Noble Victories)
title: Pokemon Card of the Day #1539: Vanilluxe (Noble Victories)
body:
Vanilluxe was a card with serious locking potential but a big reliance on coin flips as well as a type of lock that could be switched out of with Item cards. Such a Pokemon would need a bunch of support to work well. It just so happened that, in the HGSS-On format at least, said support was available. That gave it a lot of potential to be the star of a deck that bucked the trend of big attackers.

130 HP was typical for a Stage 2. It was at a nice number in a format that most of the strongest Pokemon fell just a little bit short. The Metal Weakness was rather average as far as those went. While the best decks didn’t run Metal-types too often, Klinklang decks using Cobalion were competitive and could cause problems. Vanilluxe also needed 2 Energy to retreat. You’d probably leave Vanilluxe in until it fell in most cases, but it’s worth noting nonetheless.

Double Freeze was a flip-based attack with a lot of potential. The price was a Water and a Colorless Energy and you flipped 2 coins. The attack did 40 damage for each heads, which wasn’t that great. The gem here was that you only needed 1 heads flip out of 2 to get Paralysis. The goal was to just keep chaining Paralysis and chip away at Pokemon while the opponent couldn’t do anything. That 25% chance of failure was still pretty bad, though. Victini was needed to help lower that to 6.25%, and Vileplume could help prevent switching around. It was a lot of set-up, but it was hard to break this once it was in place.

Frost Breath’s consistent damage, 60 for 2 Water Energy, wasn’t usually worth it. It was only there to get a KO on something weakened enough to fall to it.

Vanilluxe was an important part of a surprisingly competitive deck in the HGSS-On format. It could be prone to slow starts, but if it got going quickly it could cause all sorts of issues for a lot of decks. Pokemon EX could have problems here because they could get chipped down and give up multiple Prizes eventually if there wasn’t a window to get out to something else. Its relatively slow set-up kept it out of the top tier of decks, to be fair, but it was certainly tournament worthy during that time.
